@fjy , Sorry for small error in intervals, they were just mistakes in pasted queries. I also used 5 minutes earlier interval in timeseries but it's also irrelevant to the result. I corrected the issue content.
@fjy, about the filter. But I need it, it's a live system and I wanted to limit data to only a test account. 
I submitted topn and groupby queries without a filter for you, at once hoping that both run between events (no events happen between). Here is a result: 

<pre>
$ druid-query groupby_all.json ; druid-query topn_all.json
[ {
  "version" : "v1",
  "timestamp" : "2015-12-07T18:25:00.000Z",
  "event" : {
<b>    "count" : 161,
    "orientation_change" : null </b>
  }
}, {
  "version" : "v1",
  "timestamp" : "2015-12-07T18:25:00.000Z",
  "event" : {
    "count" : 1870,
    "orientation_change" : "0"
  }
}, {
  "version" : "v1",
  "timestamp" : "2015-12-07T18:25:00.000Z",
  "event" : {
    "count" : 7331,
    "orientation_change" : "1"
  }
} ][ {
  "timestamp" : "2015-12-07T18:25:00.000Z",
  "result" : [ {
    "count" : 7331,
    "orientation_change" : "1"
  }, {
    "count" : 1870,
    "orientation_change" : "0"
  }, {
<b>    "count" : 133,
    "orientation_change" : null </b>
  } ]
} ]
</pre>

Please note the difference between groups with orientation_change: null . 

@gianm , If you mean I should use longSum instead of count, then actually, I was using longSum of count in my original queries. I replaced them with counts to simplify examples for this issue submission.

